<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
  Decision <a href="/backlog/1731-workbench-resolves-block-shape-from-the-fui-maas-serve-url-n/">#1731</a>
  (parent <a href="/backlog/746-block-explorer-interactive-fui-block-workbench/">#746</a>) reframes the FUI
  <em>workbench</em> as <strong>thin UI over rendering</strong>: the FUI <code>/_maas/</code> serve endpoint
  (<a href="/backlog/1029-fui-maas-wrapper-serve-endpoint-vite-middleware-conforming-t/">#1029</a>,
  conforming to <code>servePathIR</code>) would provide <em>whatever shape the UI needs</em> for a component
  — source forms, CEM, a loadable element module, or a case example — <strong>resolved by URL</strong>,
  instead of each block hardcoding <code>load</code>/<code>create</code>/<code>cem</code>/<code>authorSource</code>
  closures inline in the workbench registry. The user-stated end-state is "URL-resolved blocks."
</p>

<h2>The finding that shrinks it</h2>
<p>
  "<em>Whatever shape</em> resolved by URL" is <strong>too broad</strong>. The <code>/_maas/</code> serve
  path is an <strong>executable-artifact origin</strong>: today it serves only loadable ES modules
  (React/Vue wrapper + live forms), cross-origin (CORS, the #1499 design), with an identity model
  (content-hash pin · immutable cache · SRI integrity · <code>javascript/html/error</code> media types only)
  that is meaningful only for evaluated bytes. Meanwhile ratified placement (#954/#1701) already settled that
  component <strong>source forms cross the #700 seam as pre-emitted build-time data</strong>
  (<code>authorModeSource.json</code>; FUI never imports the runtime <code>serve()</code>). So the four
  shape-classes classify cleanly — and only one is open.
</p>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
  <li><strong>Source forms / CEM → build-time data</strong> (settled, not a fork) — no source/CEM media type
    on the serve path; the panels read committed data, no live instance.</li>
  <li><strong>Case example → workbench demo fixture</strong> (settled) — an authored seed/config, neither a
    served artifact nor a WE emit.</li>
  <li><strong>Loadable element module → the one shape the serve path is for</strong> (open) — polyglot
    live forms are <em>forced</em> to the URL (#1499); the native form is the real choice.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Recommendation (at a glance)</h2>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
  <li><strong>Fork 1 — resolution scope: loadable modules only.</strong> The URL resolves executable
    element/wrapper modules; source/CEM stay build-time data, case examples stay workbench fixtures.
    <em>Rejected: extend the serve path to also return source-text + CEM-as-data</em> — it contradicts
    #954/#1701 and <strong>widens the protocol</strong> onto non-executable data no runtime consumer reads.
    <em>(Confidence High — near a forced invariant.)</em></li>
  <li><strong>Fork 2 — loadable-instance acquisition: split.</strong> Native primary stage via direct
    <code>import()</code> of the authoritative FUI element; polyglot React/Vue live forms via the
    cross-origin serve URL (forced by #1499); source-only blocks (#1701a) carry no loadable shape; plus an
    opt-in "as-served" secondary view for native (skeptic amendment). <em>Alternative: URL-resolve every
    live form incl. native via a thin descriptor (mints a workbench-only <code>wc-class-live</code> catalog
    form)</em> — closer to the stated "URL-resolved blocks" end-state. <em>(Confidence Med — divergent; this
    is where judgment is genuinely needed.)</em></li>
  <li><strong>Native-first.</strong> Load the platform-native artifact directly; the served projection is the
    opt-in, never the floor — the URL round-trip earns its keep only where there is a cross-origin/projection
    reason (the polyglot forms).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Prior art</h2>
<p>
  Every mature system splits <strong>executable-module resolution</strong> (a transform/serve URL, or a
  direct bundler import) from <strong>source/metadata resolution</strong> (build-time docgen data).
  <strong>esm.sh</strong>'s transform-by-param URL (<code>?target</code>/<code>?bundle</code>) serves
  executable modules; raw source is a distinct <code>?raw</code> mode. <strong>Storybook / Histoire /
  Ladle</strong> extract source + props as build-time docgen data and import the component module via the
  bundler. <strong>CEM-driven docs</strong> (Shoelace / Web Awesome) ship the manifest as a build-time data
  file. None overloads one transform-by-param URL to also return source-text or a manifest-as-data — which is
  exactly Fork 1's rejection of branch (b) and the support for Fork 2's direct-import default.
</p>

